# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **Antwerp International Gymnastics Tournament** (*Tournois International Gymnastique D'Anvers*), retrospectively regarded as the 1st Artistic Gymnastics World Championships, were held in Antwerp, Belgium, in conjunction with the 27th Belgian Federal Festival, on 14–18 August 1903.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The championships were purely team events without any individual awards.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Individual all-round scores were only introduced in 1922, with the first all-round individual men's champion being recognised in that year.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Individual apparatus scores were introduced subsequently.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] As such no actual individual medals were awarded at these games, the below rankings were conferred retrospectively.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] This brief biographical treatment was published at least as far back as 14 January 2017 on the official Facebook website of his alma mater in a photograph album, begun on 29 November 2016, containing other such brief biographical treatments of its notable alumni.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1905-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **2nd Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** were held in Bordeaux, France, in conjunction with the 31st Federal Festival of France, on April 22–23, 1905.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1905-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The championships consisted at the time only of a team event.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1905-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The individual all-round scores were introduced in 1922.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1905-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Individual apparatus scores were recognised subsequently retrospectively.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1905-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] An article published in the 10 June 2024 issue of The International Journal of the History of Sport (a peer-reviewed journal) claimed that the BFEG’s (the FIG’s predecessor) archives from before 1950 appear to have been lost.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **3rd Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** were held in Prague, Bohemia, in conjunction with the 5th Czech Sokol Slet on 30 June 1907.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] A historic signpost in the sometimes contentious politics of the sport occurred with respect to these championships.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] In a 100-year Anniversary Publication of the International Federation of Gymnastics, a past observation of Dr.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Miroslav Klinger, an honorary member of the FIG, was noted with regard to a German magazine article.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] In that FIG publication, it is written that an article in a 1907 issue of the German publication Deutsche Turnzeitung "dissuaded the non-slavic nations from participating in the international competition in Prague, by saying the competitors could be threatened by violence.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The goal of the article was to pressure the president of the European Federation into the renunciation of the Prague event.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] †=The website Gymnastics-History.com, in a blog entry about the 1907 World Championships, states that "In 125 Years of the FIG: The Story Goes on, the FIG lists Erben and Charmoille as the high bar champions.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] In other areas of this competition, also, Vidal was one of the highest scorers.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1909-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **4th Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** were held in Luxembourg, in conjunction with the 9th Federal Festival of Luxembourg, on August 1, 1909.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1909-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The countries sending teams to the games were France, Bohemia (i.e., the Czechs), Belgium, Carniola (i.e., Slovenia), and Italy.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **Turin International Gymnastics Tournament**, subsequently regarded as the 5th Artistic Gymnastics World Championships, was held in Turin, Italy, in conjunction with the 8th Italian Federal Festival of Gymnastics, on 13 May 1911.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The countries whose teams were officially scored at the tournament were Italy, France, Belgium, Slovenia, Croatia, Luxembourg and Bohemia (i.e., the Czech Sokol team).
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Romania sent a team of gymnasts to the event, but they took part in only some of the exercises, and were not scored for all events.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The championships were purely a team event without any individual awards.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Similarly, Czechoslovakia did not exist as an independent country at the time, instead Czech competitors competed under the flag of Bohemia.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The team totals were out of a maximum of 1126 points.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The 1 September 1911 issue of the magazine Sokolské besedy reported slightly different team totals for some of these teams, however the ordering was exactly the same.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] This source also reports Erben and Pitl as having placed 11th and 22nd.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1913-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **6th Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** were held in Paris, France, on the occasion of the 40th anniversary of the "Union des Societes des Gymnastique de France", on November 16, 1913.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1913-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The tournament was held at the Voltaire gymnasium on Rue Japy.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1922-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **7th Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** were held in Ljubljana, Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes (now Slovenia) on August 11–12, 1922.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1922-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] This was the first international tournament arranged under the auspices of FIG at which individual medals for all-round performance were awarded.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/1922-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] However, the individual medals for apparatus were not awarded at the 1922 tournament, those discussed below were awarded by FIG retrospectively.
[src:aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships/aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships** are the World Championships for aerobic gymnastics.
